'''Unkanji-niimasu Naramoto Shrine''' (うんかんじにいますならもとじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shikinaisha}} located in Nashimoto, {{jalink|Nara Prefecture|Q131287}}{{jalink|Ikoma District|Q971003}}{{jalink|Heguri Town|Q1346790}}. Under the {{jalink|Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534|former shrine ranking}}, it was classified as a {{jalink|Village shrine|Q134917284}} and is a {{jalink|shrine receiving offerings of sacred food and heihaku}}.

=== Overview ===
In volume five of the {{jalink|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|Sandai Jitsuroku}}, it is recorded: “On the twenty-second day of the tenth month of the third year of {{jalink|Jōgan (Japan)|Q1075635|Jōgan}} (abridged), Unkanji, unranked Naramoto Shrine, was granted Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade.”

The former shrine site was the {{jalink|guardian shrine|Q13479654}} of Unkanji Temple, about 500 {{jalink|meters|Q11573}} to the east, but when the temple was abolished in the first year of {{jalink|Meiji|Q3125096}}, it was relocated to its present location.

The {{jalink|enshrined deity|Q11591100}} is {{jalink|Kikurihime-no-Mikoto}}.

During the {{jalink|Edo period|Q184963}}, it was called {{jalink|Hakusan Gongen|Q11579578}} (thought to be associated with {{jalink|Hakusan faith|Q11579557}}), and in the Meiji period it was known as Nomata Myōjin.

The subsidiary shrine on the left side facing the main hall is the Kasuga Shrine, whose enshrined deity is {{jalink|Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto|Q2564508|Ame-no-Koyane-no-Mikoto}}. Immediately beside it is the Inari Shrine, whose enshrined deity is {{jalink|Inari Ōkami|Q719665}}.

At the offering hall outside the left fence of the shrine buildings, {{jalink|Amaterasu Ōmikami|Q455602}} and {{jalink|Hitokotonushi-no-Kami|Q10864079|Hitokotonushi}} are enshrined<ref>{{Cite book|Japanese|editor=Heguri Town History Editorial Committee|title=History of Heguri Town|publisher=Heguri Town Office|date=1976-04|ncid=BN04492478|pages=645-647}}</ref>.

A {{jalink|sacred tree}} is enshrined within the precincts.

